'''Synchesis''' (sin'-ki-sis) is a poetic term for a complicated interlocking word-order pattern in early Latin verse (e.g. the poems of Virgil and his contemporaries).

Variant spelling '''synchysis''' and '''synchisis'''

Synchesis is from Ancient Greek synkein, "to pour out together".  It appears in Latin as a loan-word from the Greek.

In Norman-French the Church Latin word became "synchicité" and was applied to plainsong with reference to the complex co-mingling of melodies.  

Originally synchesis may have had became associated with ideas of synchronisation but in time (perhaps to distinguish it from synchronise) synchesis came to be used to denote a confused mixture rather than a interlocking structure or harmonic blend.